  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does the buyer need to be in Brisbane on settlement day?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Under PEXA electronic settlement, which handles the overwhelming majority of Queensland residential settlements, neither party needs to be physically present. The buyer's solicitor and your solicitor settle the matter through the PEXA workspace, funds move electronically, and title transfers without anyone attending an office. A buyer in Sydney, Singapore or London can complete a Brisbane purchase without flying in. What does require attention is the physical handover: keys, codes, manuals and the pre-settlement inspection, because a remote buyer cannot walk into your selling agent's office on the afternoon of settlement to collect the keys."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Who collects the keys when the buyer is interstate or overseas at settlement?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The buyer nominates a representative in writing to your selling agent. The most common nominees are the buyer's appointed property manager (where the property will be rented), the buyer's buyer's-advocate or buyer's agent (where one was engaged), a family member or friend living in Brisbane, or a settlement agent contracted specifically for the purpose. Your selling agent should receive a written authority on the buyer's solicitor's letterhead naming the representative, and should sight a photo ID before releasing the keys. If no representative has been nominated by the morning of settlement, the keys typically stay in the agent's safe until the buyer arrives in Brisbane or nominates someone, with the buyer assuming the holding costs."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does the pre-settlement inspection work when the buyer is overseas?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The buyer is entitled to one pre-settlement inspection in the seven days before settlement under the REIQ contract. When the buyer cannot attend in person, they typically send their buyer's agent, their nominated Brisbane representative, a building inspector engaged for the purpose, or in the simplest case, a video call where a person on the ground walks the home and shows the buyer what they need to see. As the seller you should permit the inspection on reasonable notice and confirm to your selling agent that access can be coordinated. A remote inspection is no less binding than an in-person one, so any defects identified are still subject to the contract's defect mechanism."
      }
    }
  ]
};
